ver to imperial machinations, enabling state-sponsored population control projects that effectively disempowered women and deprived them of reproductive freedom. In this book, Aiko Takeuchi-Demirci follows the relationship between two iconic birth control activists, Margaret Sanger in the United States and Ishimoto Shizue in Japan, as well as other intellectuals and policymakers in both countries who supported their campaigns, to make sense of the complex transnational exchanges occurring around contraception. The birth control movement facilitated U.S. expansionism, exceptionalism, and anti-communist policy and was welcomed in Japan as a hallmark of modernity. By telling the story of reproductive politics in a transnational context, Takeuchi-Demirci draws connections between birth control activism and the history of eugenics, racism, and imperialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBirth controlzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aBirth controlzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aIshimoto (Katō) Shizue. 4aMargaret Sanger. 4aU.S.-Japan relations. 4abirth control. 4aeugenics. 4afeminism. 4aimperialism. 4apopulation control. 4atransnationalism. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360441440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604414.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles